statement: E1. Divisible Numbers (easy version)time limit per test4 secondsmemory limit per test256 megabytesinputstandard inputoutputstandard outputThis is an easy version of the problem. Find any pair of numbers $$$x$$$ and $$$y$$$ that satisfies the following conditions:$$$a < x \\leq c$$$, $$$b < y \\leq d$$$,$$$x \\cdot y$$$ is divisible by $$$a \\cdot b$$$.Note that required $$$x$$$ and $$$y$$$ may not exist.InputThe first line of the input contains a single integer $$$t$$$ $$$(1 \\leq t \\leq 10$$$), the number of test cases.The descriptions of the test cases follow.The only line of each test case contains four integers $$$a$$$, $$$b$$$, $$$c$$$ and $$$d$$$ ($$$1 \\leq a < c \\leq 10^5$$$, $$$1 \\leq b < d \\leq 10^5$$$).OutputFor each test case print a pair of numbers $$$a < x \\leq c$$$ and $$$b < y \\leq d$$$ such that $$$x \\cdot y$$$ is divisible by $$$a \\cdot b$$$. You are given four positive integers $a$, $b$, $c$, and $d$ where $a < c$ and $b < d$. Find any pair of numbers $x$ and $y$ that satisfy the following conditions:

* $a < x \leq c$
* $b < y \leq d$
* $x \cdot y$ is divisible by $a \cdot b$

If there are multiple solutions, print any of them. If there is no such pair of numbers, print -1 -1.

You are given four numbers. Find two numbers within specific ranges (the first number is between the first and third given number, the second number is between the second and fourth given number) such that their product is divisible by the product of the first two given numbers. If no such pair exists, print -1 -1.
